Recalling that class labels would not be available in a practical application of unsupervised learning, the outliers in this case do seem reasonably easy to detect in an unsupervised way. So in the case of supervised learning, since there is somewhat of a large separation between outleirs and the rest of the group, we can assume that a supervised strategy may also be applicable in this case, and should be able to detect the outliers as well.

library(dbscan)
k <- 5 # KNN parameter
KNN_Outlier <- kNNdist(x=PB_Predictors, k = k)[,k] # KNN distance (outlier score) computation

library(rgl)

myColorRamp <- function(colors, values) {
    v <- (values - min(knn_distance$score))/diff(range(knn_distance$score))
    x <- colorRamp(colors)(v)
    rgb(x[,1], x[,2], x[,3], maxColorValue = 275)
}

x <- knn_distance$PC1
y <- knn_distance$PC2
z <- knn_distance$PC3

cols <- myColorRamp(c("red", "blue"), knn_distance$score) 
#plot3d(x = x, y = y, z = z, col = cols)
plot3d(x = x, y = y, z = z, col = heat.colors(length(knn_distance$score))[rank(knn_distance$score)])

These plots do provide some new insights into the value of k, the diverging color scale for KNN outliers scores shows us that potential outliers are different to the rest of the cluster, and the further they are from the center of the cluster the higher the KNN outlier score.

From an unsupervised perspective, we can say that the top 31 outliers change for each new value of k, and therefore it is important to note that what may be considered an outlier for one measure of k, may not be the same for another.

ACTIVITY 3: Supervised Anomoly Detection

2. Supervised Classification on Stamps

ROCR Function

library(ROCR)
## Loading required package: gplots
## 
## Attaching package: 'gplots'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     lowess
rocplot <- function(pred, truth){
  predobj <<- prediction(pred, truth)
  ROC     <<- performance(predobj, "tpr", "fpr")
  plot(ROC)   # Plot the ROC Curve
  auc     <- performance(predobj, measure = "auc")
  auc     <- auc@y.values[[1]]
  return(auc) # Return the Area Under the Curve ROC
}

#AUC <- rocplot(pred=P_positive_test, truth=test_class_labels)

Scale Predictors as Matrix for KNN

predictors <- Stamps[,1:9]

The performances by the Supervised classifiers were different to that of the Unsupervised classifiers.

Overall, it seems that other than for where k = 5, the Supervised classification true positive rate seemed to outperform the Unsupervised classification for the same measures of k.

Where k = 5, there was a fairly low performance for both Supervised and Unsupervised classifiers. However, while comparing the best performing measure of k. 25 appears to be the optimal choice for k in terms of Supervised classification, while this is untrue for Unsupervised classification.

The highest true positive rate for Unsupervised is attained where k = 100. We can say, that based on this investigation, When the applications of class labels is unavailable, a higher measure of k is optimal for Unsupervised classification when using KNN.
